item.title: testing…123
item.description:
So this is a test, to see what other plots and stuff look like.

Let’s give naniar a spin, shall we?

library(tidyverse)
## Loading tidyverse: ggplot2
## Loading tidyverse: tibble
## Loading tidyverse: tidyr
## Loading tidyverse: readr
## Loading tidyverse: purrr
## Loading tidyverse: dplyr
## Conflicts with tidy packages ----------------------------------------------
## filter(): dplyr, stats
## lag():    dplyr, stats
library(visdat)
library(naniar)

How does visdat look?

vis_miss(airquality)

vis_dat(airquality)

And then what about some missing data plots?

ggplot(data = airquality,
       aes(x = Ozone,
           y = Temp)) + 
  geom_missing_point()

How about tables? How do they look?

summary_missing_var(airquality) %>%
  knitr::kable()
## Warning: package 'bindrcpp' was built under R version 3.3.2
variable n_missing percent
Ozone 37 24.183007
Solar.R 7 4.575163
Wind 0 0.000000
Temp 0 0.000000
Month 0 0.000000
Day 0 0.000000

And then, for fun, let’s try out treezy

library(treezy)
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)


airquality %>%
  add_prop_miss() %>%
  rpart(prop_miss ~ ., data = .) %>%
  importance_plot()

And does it deal with mathematical notation?

\[ y \sim \beta_0 + \beta_1 + \epsilon \]

What about interactive graphics?

library(plotly)
## Warning: package 'plotly' was built under R version 3.3.2
## 
## Attaching package: 'plotly'

## 
##     last_plot
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter
## The following object is masked from 'package:graphics':
## 
##     layout
ggplotly(vis_dat(airquality))
library(leaflet)
library(maxcovr)

york_crime %>%
  leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addCircleMarkers()
## Assuming 'long' and 'lat' are longitude and latitude, respectively
